      <h2>Real Talk: Is a Budget Laser Measure Good Enough?</h2>
      <p>For the majority of residential construction and renovation work, yes — absolutely. Here's the honest breakdown:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Framing:</strong> Budget is fine. ±1/8" at 50 ft is well within framing tolerances.</li>
        <li><strong>Drywall:</strong> Budget works great for room dimensions and layout.</li>
        <li><strong>Electrical:</strong> Budget is fine for box placement and conduit runs.</li>
        <li><strong>Plumbing:</strong> Budget handles rough-in measurements easily.</li>
        <li><strong>Finish Carpentry:</strong> Spring for ±1/16" accuracy — the Kiprim or POROMETISTO at budget prices will serve you well.</li>
        <li><strong>Roofing:</strong> You need range more than accuracy. The 262 ft models at budget prices work well.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Care Tips to Make Your Budget Laser Last</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Store it in the included case — dust and moisture are the #1 killers of budget lasers</li>
        <li>Clean the lens with a microfiber cloth — a dirty lens reduces range and accuracy</li>
        <li>Charge regularly (rechargeable models) — running the battery flat repeatedly shortens its lifespan</li>
        <li>Avoid dropping it on concrete — budget housings are less impact-resistant than premium models</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
      <p>The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0C76CPGC7?tag=sciencesolved-20">BOSCH GLM100-23</a> is the safest budget buy — proven reliability, great support, and enough capability for most jobs. But if you want more features without spending more, the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0GQ8V3NLP?tag=sciencesolved-20">POROMETISTO 262ft</a> and the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0FCM48QCM?tag=sciencesolved-20">Kiprim Green Laser</a> both offer exceptional value. The budget category has never been stronger — there's no excuse to be pulling a tape measure in 2026.</p>
